    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Monitoring the S.U.V.</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>W Dana Holman letter suggests taking leaf out of lawsuits against tobacco industry and suing makers of sport utility vehicles to force recalls of dangerous vehicles (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>William C. Ford Jr., the chairman of the Ford Motor Company, is worried that auto makers could wind up with reputations like those of tobacco companies if they ignore the problems of sport utility vehicles (front page, May 12).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>William C. Ford Jr., the chairman of the Ford Motor Company, is worried that auto makers could wind up with reputations like those of tobacco companies if they ignore the problems of sport utility vehicles (front page, May 12).</p>
        <p>Responsible organizations and citizens have long pointed out the destructiveness of his highly profitable vehicles. However, in his allusion to big tobacco companies, Mr. Ford has shown us a way to protect ourselves and the environment against these behemoths. Successful lawsuits have been brought against tobacco companies for manufacturing dangerous products. Makers of sport utilities should be sued, both for financial compensation and to force them to recall their damaging vehicles.</p>
        <p>W. DANA HOLMAN  Astoria, Queens, May 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
